Suppose the geometric algebra formula_101 with the familiar positive definite inner product on formula_102 is formed. Given a plane (two-dimensional subspace) of , one can find an orthonormal basis formula_103 spanning the plane, and thus find a unit pseudoscalar formula_104 representing this plane. The geometric product of any two vectors in the span of formula_105 and formula_106 lies in , that is, it is the sum of a -vector and a -vector.

By the properties of the geometric product, . The resemblance to the imaginary unit is not incidental: the subspace formula_107 is -algebra isomorphic to the complex numbers. In this way, a copy of the complex numbers is embedded in the geometric algebra for each two-dimensional subspace of formula_4 on which the quadratic form is definite.

It is sometimes possible to identify the presence of an imaginary unit in a physical equation. Such units arise from one of the many quantities in the real algebra that square to , and these have geometric significance because of the properties of the algebra and the interaction of its various subspaces.

